WEBVTT

00:01.000 --> 00:02.878
♪

00:02.878 --> 00:05.088
OLIVER PUTNAM:
We should do our own podcast.

00:05.088 --> 00:07.382
- Only Murders In The Building.

00:07.382 --> 00:08.132
- How do I know you?

00:08.132 --> 00:11.094
- Oh, Charles was in an...
an old TV series.

00:11.094 --> 00:12.513
What was it called? Bozos.

00:12.513 --> 00:13.514
- Brazzos.

00:14.139 --> 00:17.100
MABEL MORA: I have to finish this.
I have to see this through.

00:17.100 --> 00:18.435
OLIVER:
Do you like your Beats?

00:20.103 --> 00:22.022
I can't get any work.

00:22.022 --> 00:23.440
- You have to sell the apartment.

00:23.440 --> 00:24.525
- It's all I have.

00:24.525 --> 00:27.778
BUNNY: All in favor of evicting
all three members of

00:27.778 --> 00:28.737
Murder, She Wrote?

00:30.030 --> 00:31.698
- A direct route into Bunny's.

00:32.156 --> 00:34.034
- You're sleeping with a murderer!

00:34.034 --> 00:35.661
- This ends now, Jan.

00:36.870 --> 00:38.830
- Hey, Bunny! Congrats!

00:38.830 --> 00:41.458
You're the most hated person
in the building now,

00:41.458 --> 00:42.876
you cranky old bitch.

00:42.876 --> 00:45.045
[text chimes]
- "Get out of the building now."

00:45.045 --> 00:45.838
OLIVER:
Mabel!

00:45.838 --> 00:47.673
CHARLES-HADEN SAVAGE: We gotta get her!
I'm not leaving her here!

00:48.924 --> 00:50.175
- It's not what you think.

00:50.843 --> 00:52.094
OLIVER:
Bunny!

00:52.094 --> 00:53.679
- Is that your knitting needle?
- Yes!

00:53.679 --> 00:55.597
- Don't say a fucking word.

00:56.515 --> 00:58.267
POPPY:
Coming this fall,

00:58.267 --> 01:00.978
Only Murder-ers in the Building.

01:03.647 --> 01:06.650
♪ I Love New York by Steve Karmen ♪

01:11.446 --> 01:14.867
♪ I love New York ♪

01:14.867 --> 01:16.743
♪ And there's no place like it ♪

01:16.743 --> 01:18.745
CHARLES:
New York City.

01:19.288 --> 01:21.874
Who doesn't want to become
the talk of the town here?

01:21.874 --> 01:23.166
♪ I... ♪

01:23.166 --> 01:25.794
I mean, make a name
for yourself in this city,

01:25.794 --> 01:29.047
and it can feel like the most
sparkling place on Earth.

01:29.047 --> 01:31.175
WOMEN: It's that murder guy! Hey!
- Hello. [laughs]

01:31.842 --> 01:33.343
Whoa!

01:34.428 --> 01:36.680
Full of fireworks and excitement.

01:36.680 --> 01:38.640
[fireworks popping]

01:38.640 --> 01:40.726
But there are two ways
you can become known here.

01:41.602 --> 01:44.396
You can become famous
for doing good things...

01:44.396 --> 01:45.564
[popping]

01:45.564 --> 01:47.649
or you can become infamous

01:47.649 --> 01:50.652
for doing truly terrible acts.

01:50.652 --> 01:52.237
♪ 'Cause it's so exciting ♪

01:52.237 --> 01:54.406
You wanna avoid that second one.

01:54.406 --> 01:56.491
Whoa!
[fluorescent lights buzzing]

01:57.826 --> 02:00.287
- Look at you. Look at you,

02:00.287 --> 02:03.207
you dusty, old, dried-up dribble dick.

02:03.707 --> 02:07.294
You got no fuckin' idea how
much trouble you're in, do you? Hm?

02:07.294 --> 02:09.087
This guy's got no idea, huh?

02:09.087 --> 02:11.757
- None.
- You have no clue, huh?

02:11.757 --> 02:14.510
What kind of a sloppy shit-mess

02:14.510 --> 02:16.762
you chodes are swimming into, right?

02:17.596 --> 02:19.556
Right? No.
- Uh...

02:19.556 --> 02:22.601
- You know, the only thing that could be
worse for you two low-hanging,

02:22.601 --> 02:24.686
dehydrated scrota-sacks...

02:26.647 --> 02:28.065
is if you were her.

02:28.065 --> 02:31.777
Yeah, yeah, I-I-I don't do podcasts.
You know, I-I like Howard Stern.

02:31.777 --> 02:34.363
You know, old Stern,
before he started doing therapy

02:34.363 --> 02:35.656
and got all gentrified and shit.

02:35.656 --> 02:38.242
Back when it was just
the Wack Pack and Butt Bongo.

02:38.242 --> 02:41.745
Before Baba Booey got those big,
filthy teeth fixed. You know, but I, uh...

02:42.788 --> 02:45.332
I did try your podcast. Yeah. Mm.

02:45.332 --> 02:48.752
It was ab... It's absolute shit.
I mean, it really...

02:48.752 --> 02:51.213
It sucks, but this, uh,

02:51.213 --> 02:52.881
one part from the first episode...

02:54.591 --> 02:56.093
Let's just say it, uh...

02:57.719 --> 02:59.429
stuck out.
[podcast music starts playing]

02:59.429 --> 03:02.975
MABEL: [on podcast]
I have this recurring dream. I'm in bed.

03:02.975 --> 03:05.811
I wake up, and there's a man
standing over me.

03:05.811 --> 03:09.064
So, I kick him right in the nuts,
and I grab my knitting needle,

03:09.064 --> 03:10.524
and I take him down to the bone

03:10.524 --> 03:11.900
with that thing.

03:11.900 --> 03:12.901
[podcast stops]

03:13.986 --> 03:15.737
- That's you.

03:15.737 --> 03:17.239
[chair creaks]

03:17.990 --> 03:19.032
- Lawyer.

03:19.741 --> 03:21.285
- What, y-you're asking for a lawyer?

03:21.285 --> 03:24.705
- No, I'm asking if you're a lawyer,
you know, 'cause you're so smart.

03:24.705 --> 03:26.206
[Williams laughs]

03:27.249 --> 03:29.001
- [sniffs] Sorry.
- What?

03:29.001 --> 03:30.836
- No, my bad. It was a little funny.

03:30.836 --> 03:33.380
- What, her?
- W-what she said was a little funny.

03:33.380 --> 03:34.965
- What, you think
you're Rodney Dangerfield?

03:34.965 --> 03:35.966
- Oh.
- Who?

03:35.966 --> 03:36.967
- Who?

03:36.967 --> 03:38.510
- Hold on a minute!

03:38.510 --> 03:39.887
- You can't pin this on Mabel.

03:39.887 --> 03:41.430
- She couldn't have done this!

03:41.430 --> 03:42.848
WILLIAMS:
I wanna believe you.

03:42.848 --> 03:44.558
I really do.

03:44.558 --> 03:47.186
But, do you hear what you are saying?

03:47.811 --> 03:51.607
A woman magically appears,
in your apartment,

03:51.607 --> 03:53.817
with a goddamn
knitting needle in her chest?

03:53.817 --> 03:54.526
- Come on.

03:56.278 --> 03:58.447
- She--
- What? She was what?

03:59.114 --> 04:01.033
- I went to get champagne,

04:01.033 --> 04:03.493
and Bunny was just there.

04:03.493 --> 04:05.078
That's all I remember--

04:05.078 --> 04:07.831
- No. No. [sighs]
- Bullshit! This is bullshit!

04:07.831 --> 04:10.667
Mabel, there's so many
fucking holes in your story!

04:10.667 --> 04:13.212
You know, there's more
fucking holes in your story

04:13.212 --> 04:15.464
than we have in our victim,
and that's a lot of fucking holes.

04:15.464 --> 04:17.090
Eight fucking holes, to be exact.

04:17.090 --> 04:19.968
- Do you think that it makes you seem
tough saying "fuck" so much?

04:19.968 --> 04:21.303
- What?
- I mean, I get it

04:21.303 --> 04:22.888
because I used
to think the same thing,

04:22.888 --> 04:25.766
but then I realized something.
Do you wanna know what I realized?

04:27.184 --> 04:28.435
- Yeah, w-w-what did you realize?

04:29.770 --> 04:31.813
- Fuck you. Lawyer.

04:33.732 --> 04:35.943
- [sighs] Fuck.

04:35.943 --> 04:39.363
- She was gone for two minutes.
We were celebrating. W-why would she--

04:39.363 --> 04:41.198
- Okay, th-then l-l-let's
just talk about you,

04:41.198 --> 04:43.158
okay? Let-let's talk about you.

04:43.158 --> 04:44.576
You hated Bunny, right?

04:44.576 --> 04:46.578
The Board President who
wanted you out of the building

04:46.578 --> 04:48.580
'cause you couldn't pay your rent, right?

04:50.332 --> 04:53.293
- Now that I think of it,
I have had my doubts about Mabel.

04:56.213 --> 04:59.424
- You know, I played this scene
a hundred times on my show.

04:59.424 --> 05:02.511
Especially season nine
when the budget got cut,

05:02.511 --> 05:05.472
and we could only afford
to shoot in interrogation rooms.

05:05.472 --> 05:06.932
So I know your tricks.

05:06.932 --> 05:09.309
Hi! Charles-Haden Savage!

05:09.309 --> 05:10.727
- That's a decorative mirror, Charles.

05:12.104 --> 05:14.398
I think the two-way
you looking for is on this wall.

05:15.566 --> 05:17.192
- I knew that.
WILLIAMS: Mm-hmm.

05:17.192 --> 05:19.695
- [laughs]
The old decorative mirror trick.

05:21.113 --> 05:23.073
Nice try. Might have worked.

05:23.073 --> 05:24.157
On a moron.

05:24.157 --> 05:26.159
- Sit down, Charles!
- Yes, ma'am.

05:26.159 --> 05:28.495
- Let's cut to the chase now!

05:28.495 --> 05:30.205
What did you do with the knife?

05:30.205 --> 05:31.707
♪

05:31.707 --> 05:32.708
- Knife?

05:32.708 --> 05:35.252
- Yeah. What did you do with the knife?

05:35.252 --> 05:37.963
- The blade. The one you used.

05:39.965 --> 05:43.635
- So you have three people
who solved two crimes

05:43.635 --> 05:45.512
that you couldn't figure out,

05:45.512 --> 05:48.015
who are now clearly being framed,

05:48.015 --> 05:51.685
and you don't even have
the real murder weapon?

05:53.854 --> 05:56.857
♪

05:57.482 --> 06:00.611
- It was you, right? Who texted us
to get out of the building last night?

06:00.611 --> 06:02.487
- It most definitely was not me.

06:02.487 --> 06:04.698
- Gotcha. I knew it was you.

06:05.574 --> 06:08.076
- I know you did not just wink at me.
- Kinda did.

06:10.579 --> 06:12.706
- Wow! Look at this.

06:14.416 --> 06:16.460
[passing siren]
Hold it a second.

06:16.877 --> 06:18.754
They cropped me out?!

06:18.754 --> 06:20.547
This is such bullshit.

06:20.547 --> 06:22.299
You know, I'm also involved in this.

06:22.299 --> 06:25.677
- Okay, alright. Focus. All eyes on me.

06:26.678 --> 06:30.182
You are all... persons of interest now.

06:30.182 --> 06:30.974
- Thank you!

06:31.808 --> 06:33.060
WILLIAMS:
Meaning...

06:33.060 --> 06:35.395
that we can't charge you. Yet.

06:36.313 --> 06:38.315
But, that can change at any time

06:38.315 --> 06:39.816
with new evidence.

06:39.816 --> 06:41.735
And we are looking. Believe me.

06:41.735 --> 06:44.530
Because that is our jobs, not yours.

06:44.530 --> 06:47.115
So, that means no investigating,

06:47.115 --> 06:48.325
that means no fucking podca--

06:48.325 --> 06:50.619
Mora, please tell the tiny one
to stop recording me.

06:50.619 --> 06:53.080
- Oliver, put the phone down.
- Oh...

06:53.080 --> 06:55.832
- This is your ticket to live your lives.

06:55.832 --> 06:58.085
You're free to return to your homes. So,

06:58.085 --> 07:01.463
get a new hobby. Now.
I do not give a damn what it is.

07:01.463 --> 07:03.799
Just as long as it doesn't
land you in jail.

07:03.799 --> 07:06.009
- Like knitting?
- Alright, don't be a smart ass.

07:06.009 --> 07:08.595
- It's kind of her thing.
WILLIAMS: Well, your thing is going to be

07:08.595 --> 07:10.639
making toilet wine in a jail cell

07:10.639 --> 07:13.058
if you don't zip your lips. Got it? Go.

07:13.725 --> 07:15.727
Come on! Go! Now!
[clapping]

07:15.727 --> 07:17.396
♪

07:17.396 --> 07:18.397
[sighs]

07:18.397 --> 07:20.315
[reporters murmuring]

07:20.315 --> 07:21.859
[clamoring]
[shutters snapping]

07:21.859 --> 07:25.028
- [shocked] Oh my god!
- [shocked] Oh my god!

07:25.028 --> 07:26.572
- [overjoyed]
Oh my god!

07:26.572 --> 07:28.490
[chatter continues]

07:28.490 --> 07:30.534
Sweet freedom for the innocent!

07:30.534 --> 07:33.120
And justice for all crime-fighters!

07:35.080 --> 07:36.290
They were wrong!

07:36.290 --> 07:39.585
Oliver Putnam can
get arrested in this town!

07:39.585 --> 07:42.421
And, oh, baby, does that feel wonderful.
[laughs]

07:42.421 --> 07:44.965
- We're live right now!
- I'm not signing, please.

07:44.965 --> 07:47.509
I'm just like you!

07:47.509 --> 07:50.512
♪ lively theme song playing ♪

07:50.512 --> 07:53.515
♪ vocalizing ♪

08:33.555 --> 08:36.683
♪

08:38.352 --> 08:41.355
[traffic noise]
[street chatter]

08:43.899 --> 08:44.900
[elevator dings]

08:55.202 --> 08:56.203
[button clicks]

08:57.204 --> 08:58.205
[button clicks]

08:58.455 --> 08:59.456
[button clicks]

08:59.748 --> 09:02.751
[elevator doors shut]

09:08.048 --> 09:09.383
Like your Beats?

09:11.301 --> 09:13.303
- Huh?
- It's a callback

09:13.303 --> 09:15.556
because we're right back where we...

09:16.473 --> 09:17.516
Forget it.

09:19.309 --> 09:22.771
- She's not wearing Beats.
- I said forget it, didn't I?

09:24.189 --> 09:27.484
- So, uh, Bunny was just...

09:28.193 --> 09:29.862
- There, I think.

09:31.530 --> 09:33.073
- Did you see anyone else?

09:34.825 --> 09:36.285
Well, how could that be?

09:38.036 --> 09:40.038
[Oliver inhales, sighs]

09:40.747 --> 09:42.249
- Poor Bunny.

09:43.792 --> 09:45.794
I mean, my god, we...

09:46.545 --> 09:48.046
never got along, but still.

09:49.089 --> 09:51.758
[sighs] Poor Bun-Bun.

09:51.758 --> 09:53.093
[stops recording]
That plays right?

09:53.093 --> 09:54.511
I mean,
if you were on a jury, you'd buy that?

09:54.511 --> 09:56.346
- Oliver!
- You know, it's very rare

09:56.346 --> 09:58.807
for a true crime podcast to do a sequel.

09:58.807 --> 10:01.810
They usually move on to a new case
that never hits like the original,

10:01.810 --> 10:05.272
like when they followed up
the great Dead End with that, uh, Bill...

10:05.272 --> 10:08.483
- Billy the Butcher. It was terrible.
- Oh, that was the worst. Terrible.

10:08.483 --> 10:11.486
- So, you know, we have a...

10:11.486 --> 10:14.031
we have a real opportunity here.
- No, no.

10:14.031 --> 10:17.701
You heard Detective Williams.
We can't get tied into-- I can't--

10:17.701 --> 10:19.411
Oliver, stop!
[stops recording]

10:19.411 --> 10:21.914
I need a life away from death.

10:24.499 --> 10:27.169
We should all just let ourselves
be a little boring again.

10:27.169 --> 10:30.172
[ding, door opens]

10:30.172 --> 10:33.175
♪

10:36.303 --> 10:37.804
- Can I just say something?

10:38.722 --> 10:41.225
I'd rather be dead than boring.

10:41.225 --> 10:43.894
Did you guys hear that Bunny
was stabbed with a knife

10:43.894 --> 10:45.395
the cops don't have yet?
- Wait a minute,

10:45.395 --> 10:47.314
it wasn't just the knitting needle?
That's huge!

10:47.314 --> 10:48.315
- Look!

10:48.315 --> 10:50.776
Guys, maybe we could have
brunch once in a while

10:50.776 --> 10:54.196
or go watch people
play chess in the park.

10:54.196 --> 10:57.658
Whatever it is guys your age
are into besides murder.

10:59.535 --> 11:01.370
Later.

11:01.370 --> 11:03.455
[doors shut]

11:03.455 --> 11:06.041
- Well, the chess thing, yeah.
- Brunch. I'd rather have brunch.

11:07.209 --> 11:08.252
[sighs]

11:09.044 --> 11:12.047
♪

11:20.389 --> 11:22.432
[door creaks open]

11:24.226 --> 11:25.727
♪

11:33.819 --> 11:36.572
[party chatter, muffled music]

11:36.572 --> 11:37.906
- [gasps] Oh!

11:41.076 --> 11:42.578
[ragged breathing]

11:42.578 --> 11:43.453
[thud]

11:48.917 --> 11:49.918
[sighs]

11:50.627 --> 11:52.629
[water sloshing]

11:52.629 --> 11:55.632
♪

11:57.009 --> 11:58.010
[sighs]

12:08.228 --> 12:09.646
[hard scrubbing]

12:12.065 --> 12:13.567
[sighs]

12:25.370 --> 12:27.164
[phone buzzing]

12:28.332 --> 12:29.750
[phone buzzing]

12:30.250 --> 12:31.752
- Hey, Brock!

12:31.752 --> 12:33.253
Yeah, I can hold for Brock.

12:38.467 --> 12:39.885
Hey, Brock.

12:39.885 --> 12:41.887
Yeah. No, no, no.
Just for questioning.

12:43.305 --> 12:46.308
Uh, th-that probably didn't help
my chances of getting work though, huh?

12:48.685 --> 12:49.686
What?

12:49.686 --> 12:51.188
♪

12:51.188 --> 12:52.689
A reboot?

13:14.294 --> 13:17.297
♪

13:40.737 --> 13:43.490
- Hello, Mabel. This is
Alice Banks from Third Arm Gallery.

13:43.490 --> 13:45.284
We're a little artist collective downtown.

13:45.284 --> 13:47.286
Uh, maybe you've heard of us.

13:47.286 --> 13:49.788
I know this is insane,
given all you're going through,

13:49.788 --> 13:51.999
a stranger sending you
a random video message,

13:51.999 --> 13:54.668
but I really love your mural,

13:54.668 --> 13:57.212
and I haven't been able
to stop thinking about it.

13:57.713 --> 14:00.591
Uh, anyway, um,
I know this is last minute,

14:00.591 --> 14:02.384
but the gallery are having
a little opening tomorrow,

14:02.384 --> 14:04.386
and we were wondering
if you wanted to come.

14:04.386 --> 14:06.346
So... yeah.

14:06.346 --> 14:08.974
Sending you lots of love
and hope to hear from you. Bye.

14:08.974 --> 14:11.977
♪

14:32.122 --> 14:33.123
[ding]

14:34.249 --> 14:37.377
[lobby chatter]
[Oliver humming]

14:37.377 --> 14:38.378
- Come on, baby.

14:38.378 --> 14:39.922
[Winnie panting]

14:39.922 --> 14:41.465
WOMAN:
Oh, hold the elevator!

14:44.593 --> 14:46.595
Thanks, lover.
[presses button]

14:48.138 --> 14:49.515
[clears throat]
- Oh.

14:49.515 --> 14:51.058
Well, hello there, Amy Schumer.

14:51.850 --> 14:53.644
- Well, hello.

14:53.644 --> 14:55.479
[nervous laugh]
[Amy laughs]

14:55.479 --> 14:57.189
OLIVER:
Are you moving into Sting's apartment?

14:58.023 --> 14:59.233
- Uh, oh, yes!

14:59.233 --> 15:01.944
Sting. Right. Such a fan.

15:01.944 --> 15:03.278
- Oh, we all are.
- Yeah.

15:03.278 --> 15:05.447
- I loved him before
he was even in The Police.

15:05.906 --> 15:08.408
- Sting's in law enforcement?
[doors shut]

15:10.661 --> 15:12.162
- Well, welcome to the building.

15:12.162 --> 15:13.747
- Are you Oliver Putnam?

15:13.747 --> 15:16.375
- Well, that depends. Are you suing me?

15:16.375 --> 15:19.503
[both laugh]

15:19.503 --> 15:22.089
- No... I only sued Judd Apatow.

15:22.965 --> 15:25.300
Oh, and that must make you Winnie.
[Winnie panting]

15:25.300 --> 15:26.635
Oh.

15:26.635 --> 15:28.846
[baby talk]
Did we ever find out who poisoned you?

15:29.555 --> 15:31.974
[laughs] I just have to say,

15:31.974 --> 15:34.852
I really enjoyed
Only Murders In The Building.

15:34.852 --> 15:37.312
- Oh, well, thank you very much.
- No, no, no. I mean,

15:37.312 --> 15:39.940
I really enjoyed it.

15:39.940 --> 15:42.985
I was never that into murder before.

15:42.985 --> 15:46.154
Podcasts. Murder podcasts.
Until yours. But, you...

15:46.697 --> 15:48.407
you guys just made it feel so...

15:49.157 --> 15:50.868
cozy.

15:50.868 --> 15:53.161
You know? Just cozy murder. [laughs]

15:53.745 --> 15:55.497
So good.
Plus, I-I mean,

15:55.497 --> 15:58.500
y-you were so raw.
You know, all of you, and just--

15:58.500 --> 16:01.170
and not afraid of bombing.

16:01.170 --> 16:03.422
Just really wasting people's time.

16:05.757 --> 16:09.720
Reminded me of my early days
doing stand-up. Well, day.

16:09.720 --> 16:13.056
I got great pretty quick...
Is there gonna be a second season?

16:14.349 --> 16:16.768
- Well, second seasons
are tough, you know,

16:16.768 --> 16:19.354
but people keep dying.
So, I suppose there's...

16:19.354 --> 16:20.564
always a chance.

16:20.564 --> 16:22.065
[both laugh]
[ding]

16:22.858 --> 16:24.359
[laughs]
- Oh.

16:24.359 --> 16:26.737
[Winnie panting]
[both sigh]

16:26.737 --> 16:28.322
- Would you ever consider, uh...

16:29.573 --> 16:31.950
[scoffs] Never mind. It-it's stupid.

16:31.950 --> 16:34.369
- What?
- No, it-it's...

16:34.369 --> 16:36.038
I shouldn't have even
opened my tiny mouth.

16:36.038 --> 16:38.707
- Oh no, come on. What? What? What?

16:38.707 --> 16:40.626
- Okay. Well, I just had a thought...

16:41.543 --> 16:44.588
Would you ever consider selling
me the rights to the podcast,

16:44.588 --> 16:46.048
so I could turn it into

16:46.048 --> 16:48.133
an 8- to 10-episode streaming series

16:48.133 --> 16:51.428
with exclusive internet content
leading to gamification?

16:53.347 --> 16:55.015
- This is a thought you just had?

16:55.474 --> 16:58.560
- I mean, surely, you've considered
developing it into a series.

16:58.560 --> 17:00.479
- Well, I'd be lying if I didn't say

17:00.479 --> 17:02.147
I had a 200-page pitch deck

17:02.147 --> 17:04.274
floating around my apartment
somewhere. [laughs]

17:04.274 --> 17:05.734
- Okay, good!

17:05.734 --> 17:07.528
So, come by my place.
We'll figure it all out.

17:07.528 --> 17:08.529
- Okay.
- And, uh...

17:09.279 --> 17:10.739
don't forget to bring a turkey.

17:11.949 --> 17:13.242
- Oh! [laughs]

17:13.242 --> 17:15.619
- Callback!
- That's a callback. So clever.

17:15.619 --> 17:16.745
- But do bring tequila.

17:16.745 --> 17:18.288
And ice.
And a glass.

17:18.288 --> 17:21.291
♪

17:21.625 --> 17:23.627
- God, I love this building.

17:27.130 --> 17:29.466
[ship horn]
[waves lapping]

17:29.466 --> 17:32.344
- And Brazzos is doing a cross-promotion
with Golden Girls,

17:32.344 --> 17:33.971
so we go on Password,

17:33.971 --> 17:35.848
and my partner is Betty White,

17:35.848 --> 17:39.309
who turns every clue into,
like, something naughty.

17:39.309 --> 17:42.104
And I have to act outraged...

17:42.104 --> 17:43.897
[laughter]

17:43.897 --> 17:44.773
She was good people.

17:44.773 --> 17:47.442
- I could hear these stories all day.
- Mm-hmm.

17:47.442 --> 17:49.611
That's why Brazzos
is so perfect for a reboot.

17:49.611 --> 17:50.779
CHARLES:
You know, I agree with you

17:50.779 --> 17:53.115
because sometimes I'm flipping
through the TV, and I'm thinking,

17:53.115 --> 17:55.659
"Hey, where are all the cop shows?"
[laughs]

17:58.203 --> 18:00.581
'Cause th-there seems to be
a lot of cop-- Anyway,

18:00.581 --> 18:02.207
so, do you think
they're gonna go for this?

18:02.207 --> 18:05.294
- Oh. We're picked up for series already.

18:05.294 --> 18:07.588
Eighteen episodes on CBS.

18:07.588 --> 18:09.464
- Whoa!
DIRECTOR: Crazy, right?

18:09.464 --> 18:12.551
With... Naomi Jackson.

18:12.551 --> 18:13.969
CHARLES:
I love her!

18:13.969 --> 18:16.138
Who's she playing?
- She's Brazzos.

18:17.264 --> 18:18.390
- She's...

18:20.976 --> 18:22.019
And I would be...

18:22.019 --> 18:23.645
- Uncle Brazzos.

18:26.231 --> 18:27.816
- [whispers]
Uncle Brazzos...

18:29.985 --> 18:32.279
[normal] And, uh, Naomi would be my...

18:32.279 --> 18:33.280
DIRECTOR: Niece.
- Niece.

18:33.280 --> 18:34.281
- By marriage.
- Uh-huh.

18:34.281 --> 18:37.159
- Or she's a friend who affectionately
calls you "Uncle."

18:37.159 --> 18:39.494
Or something.
The writers are spit-balling.

18:39.494 --> 18:42.915
- We had you in mind
for this early on, but...

18:42.915 --> 18:44.374
honestly, we thought you were dead.

18:45.459 --> 18:48.378
The casting director had
you listed as "NA/dead."

18:48.378 --> 18:52.424
- Then you start popping up
on all the front pages

18:52.424 --> 18:55.010
of all the papers. Crazy great timing.

18:56.345 --> 18:58.013
- So...

18:58.013 --> 19:01.016
is this an offer?
I'm Brazzos again?

19:01.016 --> 19:03.644
- Uncle Brazzos.
It's a series regular.

19:04.770 --> 19:07.147
- As long as you stay out of jail.
[laughs]

19:07.147 --> 19:10.150
[laughter]

19:13.195 --> 19:15.948
[muffled music]
[street noise]

19:16.573 --> 19:19.952
♪ Look at me, look at me, butterfly,
keep it light when I get it done ♪

19:19.952 --> 19:21.245
[party chatter]

19:21.245 --> 19:24.414
♪ Look at me, look at me, double time
on the ride when I beat my drum ♪

19:25.332 --> 19:28.669
♪ Look at me, look at me, I don't stop
till I drop, yeah, keep it going ♪

19:29.336 --> 19:31.547
♪ 'Cause everybody know, everybody know ♪

19:31.547 --> 19:33.549
♪ Everybody know, everybody know ♪

19:34.800 --> 19:35.884
- Scorching.

19:35.884 --> 19:37.553
Y-you're the real deal, aren't you?

19:38.262 --> 19:40.055
- Excuse me?
- Bloody Mabel.

19:40.806 --> 19:43.308
Here. Uh, quick selfie together?
- Oh, I--

19:43.308 --> 19:45.269
- How about a quick exit? For you.

19:45.269 --> 19:47.479
Have a good night though, sir.
Thank you very much.

19:49.982 --> 19:51.024
- Thank you.

19:51.692 --> 19:54.319
Hi, Alice.
- Hi. I'm really glad you came.

19:54.319 --> 19:57.155
- I'm so glad you're not a catfish.
- Nope. No, no.

19:57.155 --> 19:58.407
All too real. [laughs]

19:59.908 --> 20:02.286
Uh, but you better watch out
for these piranhas, though.

20:03.078 --> 20:04.496
I hope you brought your knitting needle.

20:09.042 --> 20:12.546
MABEL: My dad got me a jigsaw puzzle
of Frida when I was 4.

20:13.213 --> 20:15.340
It was 1,000 pieces.

20:15.340 --> 20:18.969
Small ones with repeats
of the same flowers.

20:20.429 --> 20:23.223
I finished it the day
before I turned 5.

20:27.644 --> 20:29.938
- Sorry. There's just something...

20:29.938 --> 20:32.107
uh, very compelling about you.

20:32.107 --> 20:33.275
[laughs]

20:33.275 --> 20:34.610
- Thank you,

20:34.610 --> 20:36.695
but you don't really know
anything about me.

20:36.695 --> 20:38.697
- Well, I know four things.

20:39.823 --> 20:42.242
I know some people
are calling you Bloody Mabel,

20:42.910 --> 20:44.328
I know I like your art,

20:45.120 --> 20:47.122
I know I want that dress, and, um,

20:48.081 --> 20:50.709
now I know that you had
a Frida puzzle as a kid.

20:51.710 --> 20:54.671
- Well, all I know about you
is that you like sliding into

20:54.671 --> 20:56.548
people's DMs,

20:56.548 --> 20:58.884
and that you'd like my aunt's closet.

20:58.884 --> 21:00.802
Because that's where got this dress from.

21:00.802 --> 21:02.846
- Yes, very likely. But,

21:02.846 --> 21:04.932
I don't just DM any old broad.

21:04.932 --> 21:06.433
- Hm. Why me?

21:06.433 --> 21:07.893
- It's an instinct.

21:07.893 --> 21:10.020
And we could use some new energy
in our collective.

21:10.020 --> 21:11.980
- So, this is, what, a recruitment?

21:11.980 --> 21:14.233
- Hm. Total recruitment. How am I doing?

21:14.233 --> 21:16.026
- Decently. I might need a pamphlet.

21:16.735 --> 21:18.570
- You know, Frida didn't have an MFA.

21:19.363 --> 21:20.739
She didn't even have two working legs,

21:20.739 --> 21:23.909
but what she did have is natural talent
and everyone's attention.

21:25.577 --> 21:27.246
Remind you of anyone?

21:28.622 --> 21:31.542
[indistinct chatter]
[shutter snapping]

21:32.584 --> 21:34.920
Look, it's not a bad place to start from,

21:34.920 --> 21:36.672
as long as you have the right support.

21:36.672 --> 21:39.174
Why don't you come back
and get to know our space?

21:40.384 --> 21:41.802
- It's not a cult, right?

21:41.802 --> 21:43.720
- Just bring your paints.

21:45.347 --> 21:47.975
- I'm just gonna need to hear you say
that it's not a cult.

21:47.975 --> 21:50.686
- Mm.
- Just out loud...

21:51.478 --> 21:52.980
♪ Ain't nothing like the real thing ♪

21:53.522 --> 21:55.148
♪ Ain't nothing like the real... ♪

21:55.148 --> 21:57.484
[street chatter]

21:59.236 --> 22:00.237
[text chimes, buzzes]

22:02.114 --> 22:03.490
♪ podcast music ♪

22:03.490 --> 22:04.950
CINDA CANNING: [on podcast]
In my new podcast,

22:04.950 --> 22:06.952
Only Murderers in the Building,

22:06.952 --> 22:09.079
we will probe into the Arconia

22:09.079 --> 22:12.666
and three residents
who remain prime suspects

22:12.666 --> 22:15.377
in the grisly stabbing death
of Bunny Folger.

22:15.377 --> 22:16.670
♪

22:16.670 --> 22:19.256
Charles-Haden Savage,

22:19.256 --> 22:20.841
a washed-up television cop

22:20.841 --> 22:23.552
whose blurred sense of fact and fiction

22:23.552 --> 22:25.554
led him into a tangled romance

22:25.554 --> 22:27.890
with the last Arconia murderer,

22:27.890 --> 22:31.268
and whose father spent
the latter years of his life

22:31.268 --> 22:32.853
in and out of prison.

22:32.853 --> 22:34.354
- How do you know that?

22:34.813 --> 22:36.565
- I'm Cinda Canning, bitch.

22:37.316 --> 22:39.776
"Bloody Mabel" Mora,

22:39.776 --> 22:43.405
the freeloading 20-something who has
now been intimately involved

22:43.405 --> 22:46.783
in three grisly murders
in the same building.

22:46.783 --> 22:49.119
We will uncover the roots
of her violent past,

22:49.119 --> 22:51.205
not only as victim and witness,

22:51.205 --> 22:53.248
but also as a perpetrator.

22:53.248 --> 22:56.710
- Whatever you think you know about me,
it's not the whole story.

22:57.336 --> 22:58.921
- Girl, your crime is showing.

23:00.964 --> 23:03.342
- You've been stained. [laughs]

23:03.342 --> 23:04.468
- Poppy, we don't need that line.

23:05.636 --> 23:07.971
What are you knitting, Cindy?

23:07.971 --> 23:11.517
Oh, Indiana. That's nice.

23:11.517 --> 23:13.602
♪

23:13.977 --> 23:17.439
Oliver Putnam,
the derelict theater director

23:17.439 --> 23:21.068
who almost killed 12 people
with his last Broadway outing,

23:21.068 --> 23:24.446
has a long paper trail of
Bunny hatred over the years.

23:25.822 --> 23:26.865
Don't you?

23:28.158 --> 23:30.827
Say it, forget it. Write it, regret it.

23:30.827 --> 23:32.538
You lunatic.

23:33.247 --> 23:34.623
- You wouldn't.

23:34.623 --> 23:38.126
- Tune in weekly as our investigation
unfolds in real time.

23:39.336 --> 23:40.712
I'm Cinda Canning.

23:44.925 --> 23:46.385
- So we all heard that.

23:46.385 --> 23:48.262
- I can't believe she's investigating us.

23:48.262 --> 23:49.972
- And real time, too.

23:49.972 --> 23:52.432
I mean, she's stealing our format.

23:52.432 --> 23:54.226
We did invent that format, right?

23:54.226 --> 23:57.271
- What, the format where we drop
a true crime podcast

23:57.271 --> 23:59.439
before we even have a story,

23:59.439 --> 24:01.066
an ending, or even a crime?

24:01.066 --> 24:02.526
Yeah, that's all us.

24:02.526 --> 24:04.695
- You know, Cinda Canning is very lucky

24:04.695 --> 24:07.489
that my attorney passed away.
- I thought you said he was disbarred.

24:07.489 --> 24:10.075
- This is no time for semantics, Charles!

24:10.075 --> 24:11.618
She's stealing our format!

24:11.618 --> 24:13.704
- Cinda doesn't even know
what happened that night.

24:15.581 --> 24:16.999
- What did happen that night?

24:17.875 --> 24:19.835
- It's all a blur.

24:19.835 --> 24:22.421
♪

24:22.421 --> 24:24.548
Except...
- Except?

24:27.634 --> 24:29.636
- I think Bunny said something.

24:30.554 --> 24:32.055
[party chatter, muffled music]

24:33.348 --> 24:34.683
[gasps] Oh!

24:36.393 --> 24:38.228
- [gagging] 14...

24:38.228 --> 24:39.855
[panting]

24:39.855 --> 24:41.356
BUNNY/MABEL:
14.

24:41.356 --> 24:43.192
- 14?

24:43.859 --> 24:45.360
What does that mean?

24:45.360 --> 24:47.738
- Okay, people, we know
what we have to do.

24:47.738 --> 24:50.407
We need to go full "OliMabel" here.

24:50.407 --> 24:51.491
- What the fuck?
- What?

24:51.491 --> 24:54.494
- OliMabel! That's our ship name.
All our names put into one.

24:54.494 --> 24:56.288
- Where is the "Charles" in "OliMabel"?

24:56.288 --> 24:57.331
- The Charles is silent.

24:57.331 --> 24:59.166
Okay, so what we need to do

24:59.166 --> 25:00.918
is break into Bunny's apartment.

25:00.918 --> 25:02.002
- What?
- What?

25:02.002 --> 25:05.255
- We slip in real quick,
we find a clue that isn't us,

25:05.255 --> 25:06.673
and then Cinda has nothing!

25:06.673 --> 25:08.675
- We can't be seen
breaking into Bunny's apartment!

25:08.675 --> 25:10.385
Cinda finds that out, everything blows up.

25:10.385 --> 25:13.222
- Yeah, well, our lives blow up
if we all go down for this.

25:13.222 --> 25:15.766
And I sure as hell can kiss
Amy Schumer goodbye.

25:17.351 --> 25:20.312
Schumer moved into Sting's place.
We're talking projects.

25:20.312 --> 25:22.189
I-I'll tell you during the OliMabel.

25:22.189 --> 25:25.108
- Okay, you know you're not using
that remotely correctly?

25:25.108 --> 25:26.777
- It has gotten away from me, yes.

25:26.777 --> 25:28.779
- And I can't lose Brazzos either.

25:29.488 --> 25:32.115
- What?
- They're rebooting Brazzos.

25:32.115 --> 25:35.244
- Charles! You're Brazzos again!
- Oh my god! That's fantastic!

25:35.244 --> 25:37.746
- I am. Yeah, well, you know,
Uncle Brazzos.

25:37.746 --> 25:39.665
Kind of a sexy Uncle Brazzos.

25:39.665 --> 25:41.208
You know, they keep wanting
that beefcake thing from me.

25:42.417 --> 25:43.669
And they have writers, multiple writers!

25:43.669 --> 25:44.837
Not just some executive producer,

25:44.837 --> 25:47.881
high on cocaine,
screaming dialogue into a tape recorder.

25:47.881 --> 25:49.174
It's real.

25:49.174 --> 25:51.468
- Mabel, don't you want to
clear your name, too?

25:53.303 --> 25:56.014
- Look, what Cinda said wasn't wrong.

25:56.014 --> 25:59.685
My whole life has been
defined by this crap.

25:59.685 --> 26:00.686
Death.

26:00.686 --> 26:02.729
Walking around blood.

26:03.438 --> 26:06.275
I'd like to try and be an artist.

26:07.317 --> 26:10.153
And last night, for a few minutes,

26:10.153 --> 26:12.281
that felt maybe possible.

26:14.199 --> 26:17.119
So, if it takes clearing my name

26:17.119 --> 26:18.787
to feel that more

26:18.787 --> 26:20.497
and finding who really did this--

26:20.497 --> 26:22.499
BUNNY: [muffled]
Fuck off, Oliver.

26:25.669 --> 26:27.629
Fuck off, Oliver.
- I'm sorry. I--

26:27.629 --> 26:29.798
BUNNY: Fuck off.
[snorts]

26:29.798 --> 26:32.384
- Is that Bunny?
- Are you hearing that, too?

26:33.302 --> 26:34.553
MABEL:
Yeah.

26:34.553 --> 26:37.556
♪

26:38.599 --> 26:39.975
BUNNY [echoing]
Fuck off.

26:43.478 --> 26:45.981
- No one has to see us breaking in.

26:49.193 --> 26:50.694
[Oliver groans]

26:50.694 --> 26:53.530
[vent rattling]
OLIVER: Shit... How do I...

26:53.530 --> 26:54.823
MABEL: Just kick it!
CHARLES: Kick it!

26:56.200 --> 26:57.451
OLIVER:
Oh! Look at that.

26:58.577 --> 27:00.287
[groans]
CHARLES: Quiet!

27:00.287 --> 27:01.997
OLIVER:
Oh!

27:02.748 --> 27:04.124
Ah!
[thud]

27:04.124 --> 27:06.251
MABEL: Shh!
[Oliver groaning]

27:06.793 --> 27:08.670
- [sniffs] Oh my god.

27:08.670 --> 27:10.923
The last time I was in a space that small,

27:10.923 --> 27:12.466
I'd had too many Cosmos in Vegas

27:12.466 --> 27:15.219
and ended up on stage
with Penn and Teller.

27:15.219 --> 27:17.262
[laughs] You know, they were
about to saw me in half,

27:17.262 --> 27:20.098
and m-my bladder was so full,
so I felt like an idiot, but I didn't--

27:20.098 --> 27:22.142
- Okay, I really am good
with this story right now.

27:22.142 --> 27:24.144
- Alright.
- Thank you! Me, too!

27:25.229 --> 27:27.272
[vent rattling]

27:27.272 --> 27:28.857
♪

27:28.857 --> 27:30.108
MABEL [quietly]
Bunny?

27:31.360 --> 27:32.611
Bunny?

27:32.611 --> 27:34.571
[rattling]
Hello?

27:34.571 --> 27:36.156
BUNNY:
Get out.

27:37.449 --> 27:38.450
- Go.

27:40.702 --> 27:42.037
BUNNY:
Get out!

27:42.037 --> 27:43.872
[flapping, squawk]

27:43.872 --> 27:46.291
[gasps]
- Bunny had a bird?

27:46.291 --> 27:48.961
- Still?
- Still?

27:48.961 --> 27:50.462
You knew she had a bird?

27:50.462 --> 27:52.464
- Well, I mean, she got it decades ago

27:52.464 --> 27:54.842
when birds were the hot pet,

27:54.842 --> 27:56.677
before teacup pigs stole their mojo.

27:56.677 --> 27:58.720
I just assumed it was dead.

27:58.720 --> 28:01.139
- Yellow-headed amazon. Beautiful.

28:01.139 --> 28:02.558
- Stuff it up your ass.

28:03.433 --> 28:05.727
- Well, it's definitely
got Bunny's potty mouth.

28:05.727 --> 28:07.062
- Mm-hmm.
- Kinda makes me miss her.

28:07.563 --> 28:09.022
- Mrs. Gambolini.

28:09.022 --> 28:10.816
MABEL: Who's that.
- Oh, that's the bird.

28:10.816 --> 28:13.235
Remember, Bunny was a freak.
[squawks]

28:13.861 --> 28:15.320
So listen, listen.

28:15.320 --> 28:18.740
Since we are here, why don't we
just split up and search around?

28:18.740 --> 28:21.118
Keep your eyes open for anything
that resembles a note.

28:21.743 --> 28:23.996
- Note?
- Well, notes. [nervous laugh]

28:23.996 --> 28:26.039
I may have written a few
I'd like to retrieve.

28:26.707 --> 28:29.877
Like, basically, how I wanted Bunny to die
when she was trying to evict us.

28:29.877 --> 28:31.461
- Oh, smart. Real smart.

28:31.461 --> 28:34.464
Because, you know, death threats
always work out really well.

28:34.464 --> 28:37.634
- Okay, start scouring.
Any paper you find, put in this bag.

28:38.218 --> 28:39.803
- I'll go in the bedroom.

28:39.803 --> 28:41.471
♪

28:41.471 --> 28:43.849
MABEL: Okay.
- Alright. Quickly, quickly.

28:43.849 --> 28:47.060
- I got this.
- Anything, anything with my name on it...

28:47.060 --> 28:49.813
Look at this.
Let's put this in here too.

28:51.899 --> 28:53.567
Okay!

28:53.567 --> 28:55.903
[door unlocking]

28:55.903 --> 28:57.237
Oh...
- Shit!

28:57.863 --> 28:59.114
[click]
OLIVER: Come on!

29:00.991 --> 29:02.576
[loud whisper]
Charles! Charles!

29:02.576 --> 29:04.494
Someone is coming!
[muttering]

29:05.621 --> 29:06.663
[door squeaks]

29:08.749 --> 29:11.585
- Bunny had a real eye for erotic art.

29:11.585 --> 29:13.128
A lot of people didn't know that.

29:13.128 --> 29:15.380
- [loud whisper] I think it's Uma.
HOWARD: I'm not surprised.

29:15.380 --> 29:16.715
Bunny was a fuckin' freak.

29:16.715 --> 29:17.966
- And Howard.

29:17.966 --> 29:19.885
UMA:
This Rose Cooper painting that she has,

29:19.885 --> 29:21.470
it's very porny.

29:21.470 --> 29:22.638
[mouthing]

29:22.638 --> 29:24.640
A naked man wrapped around a woman's leg.

29:24.640 --> 29:26.517
Very balls forward.

29:26.517 --> 29:28.352
- Mm. Maybe I'll own one someday.

29:28.352 --> 29:30.479
- Oh, fat chance. It's worth a fortune.

29:30.479 --> 29:31.980
We need to wrap it up,

29:31.980 --> 29:33.899
so I can take it to the appraiser.

29:33.899 --> 29:35.984
It's in the bedroom here.
- They're coming this way!

29:35.984 --> 29:36.985
- Come in here!

29:36.985 --> 29:39.905
♪

29:39.905 --> 29:41.490
[coat hangers rattling]

29:41.490 --> 29:43.575
- I'm telling you,
this thing is one of a kind.

29:43.575 --> 29:44.993
This could be worth a million...

29:46.703 --> 29:48.163
[screaming]

29:48.163 --> 29:50.832
[both screaming]

